Just coming to you with an important Christmas public service announcement üôãüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüëãüèº
This week you‚Äôll probably be inundated with content telling you how to handle the festive season. Some will share workouts to ‚Äúburn off‚Äù your mince pies and low calorie Christmas cake recipes. Others will encourage you to let loose at the buffet and embrace the sloth life ü¶•
And what‚Äôs my opinion?
Do whatever the hell you want üíÅüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
Whether you want to stay active or settle into the sofa, do that. Whether you want to get boozy or stay teetotal, do that. Whether you want to watch your portions or go hard at Christmas dinner, do that. Health looks different to everyone and I‚Äôm not here to dictate what is best for you or what your body and mind needs, only you know that üôåüèº
And me? 
I‚Äôll be tucking into all the delicious festive food and snuggling under a blanket, but also eating lots of plants and staying active. Because it‚Äôs possible to do both ü•∞üå±
Ultimately, you do you boo. Let‚Äôs not judge each other this Christmas ‚ù§Ô∏è

Festive Bubble & Squeak Cakes üòãüå± AD

2‚É£ Throw all the sprouts and half the squash into a bowl with 2 tbsp of flour and mash until combined. 
3‚É£ Blend the remaining butternut squash into a pur√©e to serve alongside the cakes.

5‚É£ Place a few handfuls of @strongrootsuk winter greens into a small saucepan and allow to wilt down whilst the cakes are cooking.

5 ways to be a little bit more conscious this Christmas üéÖüèºü•∞
1Ô∏è‚É£ Lets talk trees. You need to use a artificial tree for 30+ years for it to balance out its footprint - so only invest if you‚Äôre keeping it for the long term. If you go for a real one, you can always rent a tree and have it collected after Christmas and re-planted! Try and opt for FSC & Soil Association certified trees and if you didn‚Äôt rent one, try to ensure it is disposed of responsibly by seeking out a local tree recycling scheme. üéÑ 
2Ô∏è‚É£ Eat more plants. Plant based meals are lower impact and can be absolutely delicious. You don‚Äôt have to go ‚Äúcold turkey‚Äù - pardon the pun! - but just cutting down on your animal product consumption helps reduce the footprint of your meals as well as animal suffering üå±
3Ô∏è‚É£ Wrap responsibly. Avoid shiny & un-recyclable wrapping paper. You can upcycle newspaper, use recyclable brown paper or even reuse wrapping you‚Äôve been given before. I like to give my gifts in pretty bags which can be passed on again and again. üíù
4Ô∏è‚É£ Avoid food waste. 7.9 million slices of turkey and 7.5 million mince pies go to waste each year in the UK alone. Use your leftovers by popping them in a soup or a Christmas sarnie. Compost anything else ü¶É
5Ô∏è‚É£ Shop small. By less and buy better. Less tat and more gifts which are low waste, experience based or sourced from a small sustainable business üéÅ 
These are a great place to start, but of course there are many amazing sustainable swaps we can make at this time of year! üôåüèº
What is your top conscious Christmas tip? Leave it in the comments below! ‚ù§Ô∏è

Should food labels include the amount of exercise needed to burn them off? ü§î
I am on ITV News today discussing the new study which suggests this as a potential solution to rising obesity levels. In case you can‚Äôt tune in at 1.30pm then here‚Äôs the main thoughts I shared:
‚û°Ô∏è Food is so much more than calories. It‚Äôs micro and macro nutrients, it‚Äôs energy, it‚Äôs enjoyment and it‚Äôs fuel. It is a reductionist approach to focus on calories (or calories burned) alone.
‚û°Ô∏è Everyone processes food differently and exercise intensity is subjective, so a blanket exercise target or duration won‚Äôt be relevant to everyone.
‚û°Ô∏è This has the potential to lead to unhealthy relationships with food. It enforces an ‚Äúearn and burn‚Äù mentality where food is seen as something to earn and exercise is seen as a punishment for what we eat. Surely we should encourage more positive approaches to healthy living? And ones which avoid negative emotions such as guilt?
‚û°Ô∏è Overall, I respect that researchers are trying to find new and innovative approaches to encouraging us to move our bodies, but personally I don‚Äôt think this is the best solution.
What are your thoughts?
Let me know in the comments! ü•∞‚ù§Ô∏è #itvnews #dietculture #healthylifestyle #igfitness #fitnessmotivation #fitnessjourney #gettinghealthy #healthyliving #caloriecounting

Note to self: people don‚Äôt like me, and that‚Äôs ok! It might even be a good thing üíÅüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
I know people don‚Äôt like me. Online they message me, leave a comment or simply unfollow me. I‚Äôm confronted with this fact every day and as someone who is a people pleaser, at times it has been a massive headf*ck üò¨
HOWEVER. I am here to tell you what I tell myself. The reasons why it is totally ok to not be liked by everyone. 
1Ô∏è‚É£ It is impossible to make everyone like you. I have friends who are INCREDIBLE humans, yet people still don‚Äôt like them. It blows my mind. You just can‚Äôt please everyone no matter how lovely you are.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Being disliked means you‚Äôre not sitting on the fence, you‚Äôre not middle of the road. You stand for something, you challenge others opinions, you shift perspectives. You‚Äôre divisive and not everyone likes that. 
3Ô∏è‚É£ Nobody else truly knows your full story, they‚Äôre judging you based on limited knowledge of who you are and what you‚Äôve been through.
4Ô∏è‚É£ I‚Äôm not keen on some people, but I would never tell them. For someone to take the time out of their day to send you negativity, that‚Äôs a reflection of their own issues.
5Ô∏è‚É£ Really, who cares? So what someone doesn‚Äôt like you. But tonnes of other people do! Shake it off, you know you‚Äôre a good human and THAT is what matters üëèüèº
This is just a reminder that it is perfectly ok that not everyone likes you. You are more than enough for those who love you ‚ù§Ô∏è
Post inspired by @jera.bean üôåüèº
